docs.abstract: An appeals court ruling provides a few clues but no real answers to a sealed court fight that some speculate involves Robert S. Mueller III, the special counsel.
docs.snippet: An appeals court ruling provides a few clues but no real answers to a sealed court fight that some speculate involves Robert S. Mueller III, the special counsel.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A mystery witness fighting a secret fight over a sealed subpoena with a prosecutor who may be Robert S. Mueller III, the special counsel investigating the Trump-Russia affair, turns out to be a corporation owned by a foreign government, according to a federal appeals court ruling on Tuesday.

headline.main: Washington’s Mystery Witness Turns Out to Be a Corporation, Not a Person
headline.print_headline: Mystery Witness in Inquiry Is an Overseas Corporation

docs.abstract: Senate Democrats said they would never accede to President Trump’s demand for $5 billion for a border wall, and the White House offered no early indication that the president would accept less.
docs.snippet: Senate Democrats said they would never accede to President Trump’s demand for $5 billion for a border wall, and the White House offered no early indication that the president would accept less.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As the White House and Democrats remained locked in a standoff over funding for President Trump’s border wall, Senator Mitch McConnell, the Republican leader, sent his colleagues home for the Christmas holiday on Saturday, virtually ensuring that the government will remain partially shuttered for at least several more days.

headline.main: Government Shutdown to Continue for Days as Senate Adjourns Until Thursday
headline.print_headline: Shutdown Is Set To Last for Days As Trump Digs In

byline.original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Katie Rogers

docs.abstract: With funding now lapsing for nine departments and several federal agencies, the president remained in Washington, reiterating his demand for a border wall.
docs.snippet: With funding now lapsing for nine departments and several federal agencies, the president remained in Washington, reiterating his demand for a border wall.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump invited reporters into the Oval Office on Christmas morning to listen to him call military troops overseas. He then unleashed another demand for a border wall — a $5 billion price tag that has stalled the federal government through the holidays — and introduced a murky new claim that federal workers are happy to work for free until the wall is fully funded.

headline.main: Trump’s Christmas Message: ‘It’s a Disgrace What’s Happening’
headline.print_headline: Christmas in the Oval Office: Messages For the Troops, and More Talk of a Wall

byline.original: By Katie Rogers and Emily Cochrane

docs.abstract: The question is at the heart of investigations by Congress and federal agencies into whether an American gun manufacturer is entangled in the shadowy world of arms smuggling and wildlife poaching.
docs.snippet: The question is at the heart of investigations by Congress and federal agencies into whether an American gun manufacturer is entangled in the shadowy world of arms smuggling and wildlife poaching.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOEDSPRUIT, South Africa — High-powered hunting rifles are the tools of the trade for poachers in South Africa and Mozambique. Steady and deadly accurate, the rifles are capable of dropping a rhinoceros with one shot from long distances, and are a major reason the rhinos in those African countries, highly valued for their horns, are dwindling toward extinction.

headline.main: How Did Rifles With an American Stamp End Up in the Hands of African Poachers?
headline.print_headline: When American Rifles End Up in the Hands Of Poachers in Africa

docs.abstract: Hours before a midnight deadline, White House officials and senators unsuccessfully scrambled to cut a deal to avert a partial government shutdown.
docs.snippet: Hours before a midnight deadline, White House officials and senators unsuccessfully scrambled to cut a deal to avert a partial government shutdown.
docs.lead_paragraph: • The Senate and House have adjourned without reaching a deal. The government will partly shut down after funding expires at midnight.

headline.main: Government to Shut Down: House and Senate Adjourn With No Spending Deal

docs.abstract: Funding for nine federal departments and several agencies is set to expire at midnight Friday. For now, hopes of avoiding a shutdown seem faint.
docs.snippet: Funding for nine federal departments and several agencies is set to expire at midnight Friday. For now, hopes of avoiding a shutdown seem faint.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hours away from a partial government shutdown, here’s where things stand — and how we got here.

headline.main: A Possible Government Shutdown? Here’s Where Things Stand

docs.abstract: A federal appeals court issued a stay blocking subpoenas seeking documents from the Trump Organization and the president’s trust. A hearing was scheduled for March.
docs.snippet: A federal appeals court issued a stay blocking subpoenas seeking documents from the Trump Organization and the president’s trust. A hearing was scheduled for March.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A federal appeals court temporarily halted on Thursday a lawsuit that accuses President Trump of illegally benefiting from his family’s business, an interim victory for the Justice Department in its effort to block more than three dozen subpoenas for documents from the Trump Organization, the president’s trust and other entities.

headline.main: Court Temporarily Halts Emoluments Suit Against Trump

docs.abstract: The defense secretary and other administration officials are described as resorting to extraordinary measures to thwart the president’s decisions in a White House depicted as “crazytown.”
docs.snippet: The defense secretary and other administration officials are described as resorting to extraordinary measures to thwart the president’s decisions in a White House depicted as “crazytown.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump so alarmed his defense secretary, Jim Mattis, during a discussion last January of the nuclear standoff with North Korea that an exasperated Mr. Mattis told colleagues “the president acted like — and had the understanding of — a ‘fifth or sixth grader.’”

headline.main: Jim Mattis Compared Trump to ‘Fifth or Sixth Grader,’ Bob Woodward Says in Book
headline.print_headline: Woodward’s Sprawling Exposé Depicts White House in Chaos

docs.abstract: Buffeted by a drop in the markets, fallout over his troop pullout and a looming shutdown, the president is forced to test the idea that he is his own best spokesman.
docs.snippet: Buffeted by a drop in the markets, fallout over his troop pullout and a looming shutdown, the president is forced to test the idea that he is his own best spokesman.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump, who has long believed that he is his own best adviser and spokesman, was forced to test that idea on Friday when few of his allies seemed willing to publicly share in his evident satisfaction with the tumultuous events that have buffeted the White House in the past few days.

headline.main: Reliable Allies Refuse to Defend a President Content With Chaos
headline.print_headline: Confusion and Controversy Swirl,  But the President Remains Positive

byline.original: By Katie Rogers and Maggie Haberman
